# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The Jump Game is a type of dynamic programming problem. The purpose is to determine if it is possible to reach the index in an array by jumping from index to index. The number at each index represents the maximum steps that can be jump from that index.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
There are many approaches to this problem. The most simple and efficience approach is to use `Greedy Algorithm`. If you want to check out for different approach please check the code and explanation in the #Code Section

1. Create a variable called `lastPos` initialized to last index of the array. 
2. Iterate the array from the second last index to the first index, checking if the current index `k` + `nums[k]` is greater than or equal to the distance to the `lastPos` index. If so, update the `lastPos` index to the current index.
3. Return true if the first index is greater than or equal to the distance to the `lastPos` index, else return false.



# Code
#### **1) Brute force solution (Recursive) [TLE] ❌**
The idea is to start from the first index and try every possible jump from that index, checking if the jump leads to the end of the array. The`DFS` takes in 2 parameters, the `nums` array and the current index position `index`. 

```
class Solution {
    public boolean canJump(int[] nums) {
        return DFS(nums, 0);
    }
    public boolean DFS(int [] nums, int index)
    {

        if(index >= nums.length-1) return true;
        if(nums[index] == 0) return false;
        //this is the part where it would lead to a TLE.
        int jump = nums[index];
        boolean result = false;
        while(jump > 0)
        {
            result = result || DFS(nums, index  + jump);
            jump--;
        }    
        return result;
    }
}

```
- Time complexity: $$O(2^n)$$ in the worst case, where n is the number of elements in the array. For each jump, the algorithm tries every possible jump length and this leads to an exponential number of possible paths to explore.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$ where n is the maximum depth of the recursion tree, which is equal to the length of the input array.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


#### **Optimized version:**
Using the same code above, instead of storing the current index in variable `jump`, I decrement the `nums[index]` after checking it. The reason is if that index position has been checked for all possible jumps, the value in the array will be set to 0. Which will not be checked later if we backtrack to try another jump from the previous index.

```
class Solution {
    public boolean canJump(int[] nums) {
        return DFS(nums, 0);
    }
    public boolean DFS(int [] nums, int index)
    {

        if(index >= nums.length-1) return true;
        if(nums[index] == 0) return false;
        boolean result = false;
        while(nums[index] > 0)
        {
            result = result || DFS(nums, index  + nums[index]);
            nums[index]--;
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```
- Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$ in the worst case, where n is the number of elements in the array. 
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$ where n is the maximum depth of the recursion tree, which is equal to the length of the input array.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->



#### **2) Dynamic programming solutions**
##### 1. Recursive - Memoization - Top Down ✅

When calculating, we might end up at the same index again. By creating an array call `dp`, we store `true` if that index has been processed earlier. In the case which we encountered this index again, we will return false.


```
class Solution {
    public boolean canJump(int[] nums) {
        boolean [] dp = new boolean[nums.length];
        return DFS(nums, 0,dp);
    }
    public boolean DFS(int [] nums, int index, boolean [] dp)
    {
       if(index >= nums.length-1) return true;
       if(dp[index] == true) return false;
       dp[index] = true;
       int jump = nums[index];
       if(jump == 0) return false;


        for(int k = jump; k >= 1; k--)
        {
            if(DFS(nums, index + k,dp))
            {   
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
}
```
- Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$ in the worst case, where n is the length of the nums array.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$ where n is the maximum depth of the recursion tree, which is equal to the length of the input array. This is because we need to store the dp array which has n elements.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


##### 2. Iterative - Tabulation - Bottom Up ✅

The dea behind this solution is to iterate through the `nums` array from the end to the start and keep track of the last position that can be reach. 

Here a steps to understand this problem:

Step 1 - First, we initialize a boolean array `dp` of length `nums.length` with the last element of the dp array set to true.

Step 2 - Next, a loop is used to iterate backwards from the second to last element `nums.length-2` to the first element `0`.

Step 3 - For each iteration, a variable `furthestJump` is intialized to hold the maximum jump possible from the current position. You may ask why it compares the min of `k + nums[k]` and `nums.length - 1`. Think about an array containing [1,4,1,1]. At position `k = 1`, the maximum jump distance is `1 + nums[1] = 1 + 4 = 5`. However this distance goes beyond the length of they array (4). So the actual maximum jump distance from position `k = 1` is `4`. The distance is stored in the `furthestJump` variable and used to control the range of the inner loop.

Step 4 - A nested loop is then used to iterate from `k + 1` to `furthestJump`. If dp[j] is true (meaning it is possible to reach the end of the array from position j), then set dp[k] to true (since it is now possible to reach the end of the array from position k), and break out of the nested loop.

Step 5 - Finally, return the value of dp[0] which indicates whether it is possible to reach the end of the array from the start (dp[0] being true means it is possible, dp[0] being false means it is not possible).


```
class Solution {
    public boolean canJump(int[] nums) {
        boolean [] dp = new boolean[nums.length];
        dp[nums.length-1] = true;
        for(int k = nums.length-2; k >= 0; k--)
        {
            int furthestJump = Math.min(k + nums[k], nums.length-1);
            for(int j = k + 1; j <= furthestJump; j++)
            {
                if(dp[j] == true) 
                {
                    dp[k] = true;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[0];
    }
}
```

- Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$ where n is the length of the array. This is because we make two passes through the array, one from `nums.length-2` to 0 and one inner loop that goes from `k + 1` to the `furthestJump`
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$ where n i s the length of the array because we use a `dp` array of length `n` to keep track of the result.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

##### 3. Greedy Solution ✅

This solution is built on top of the previous solution. This one has a time complexity of $$O(n)$$ and a space complexity of $$O(1)$$.

By keeping track of the last position that can be reached by starting from the end of the array. We can return true if the last position that can be reached is the first index (which is 0). Otherwise, we can just return false.

```
class Solution {
    public boolean canJump(int[] nums) {
        int lastPos = nums.length-1;
        for(int k = nums.length - 2; k >= 0; k--)
        {
            if(k + nums[k] >= lastPos)
            lastPos = k;
        }
        return lastPos == 0;
    }
}
```

- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$ where n is the length of the array.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$ because we only need to store a single variable `lastPos` to keep track of the last position that can be reached.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Application

###### The Jump Game problem have several real-life applications, including the following: 
1. Game Development: model the movement of a character in a 2D game, where the character need to jump over an obstacle to reach the end of the level.
2. Robotics: the Jump Game problem can be applied to robotic motion planning, where a robot needs to determine the optimal path to reach a destination by jumping over obstacles.
3. Network Routing: model the process of finding a path in a network, for example, computer network or a transportation network, where nodes represent the index of the array and edges represent the jumps between nodes.
4. Financial Investment: whenever an investor needs to determine if they can reach the target value by making a series of investments, with each investment representing a jump in the array.



